 "coaching": {
  "headline": "Two Orb Primes taken, both wasted \u2014 a 47-minute loss with the structure war lost 6 to 14. You owned the prime pit and never cashed it into the map.",
  "team": "Trio of you (Goldilocks/Xeebs/Willy) on Murdock-carry, Bayle-offlane, Zinx-support, plus two randoms on TwinBlast mid and Grux jungle. The draft wasn't the problem: jungle was favored (Grux 51.5% into Yin), support even (Zinx 50.3%), and the three lanes only a hair behind on pred.gg \u2014 Murdock 48.4% into Sparrow, TwinBlast 48.5% into Fey, Bayle 47.6% into Steel. Roughly even on paper. You won the objective pit \u2014 mini-prime at 16, Orb Prime at 28 AND 42 \u2014 and still lost structures 6 to 14 and got out-damaged on buildings 57k to 125k. That's the whole game: prime buffs that never became towers. Two things bled it out. First, the two randoms fed \u2014 Grux 9 deaths (his norm is 3) and TwinBlast 6 (norm 2), 15 deaths between them, every one handing the map back while you held the buff. Second, damage profile: you're 4/5 physical, so one armor item blunts most of you, while Fey did 81k magic and exactly one of five of you bought magic resist. You poked, they sieged.",
  "whatShiftedIt": "After Orb Prime the clock IS the buff \u2014 group five and break a tower lane immediately, don't go fish for picks into Riktor's chain-CC (pull\u2192silence\u2192suppress, ~2.5s) while it ticks away. Either of those two primes converted into structures wins this. And someone past Zinx needs a magic-resist item \u2014 Fey's 81k went unanswered. Anti-heal was fine; you brought two and Riktor's the only sustain, so don't spend the post-game on it.",
  "perPlayer": {
   "16f28434-561f-4f23-9454-40321f4a1ef3": "Murdock carry, 7/5/2 \u2014 best damage on the team and the matchup into Sparrow is a coin-flip (48.4%), so this was yours to carry and you nearly did. Two fixes: 5 deaths vs your 3 norm means you got caught chasing out of position, and you skipped Lightning Hawk \u2014 the 53% core opener over 346 games. As the main threat on a 4/5-physical team that the enemy answers with a single armor piece, you need the crit/attack-speed spike from the core, not extra raw AD off Necrosis/Spear.",
   "a412baf3-dd17-4f89-8ecf-9d0704f3a79e": "Bayle offlane, 4/5/6 \u2014 deaths in line with your norm, so no feeding here; the build is the miss. You ran Mutilator/Sky-Splitter/Tainted-Rounds/Salvation/Aegis and skipped the entire winning core (Overlord/Rapture/Cursed Scroll, 56% over 131). Bayle into Steel is already a hair behind (47.6%) and off-core makes it worse. Your Kingslayer knockback is half the team's hard CC \u2014 build to be the front that opens the fight on the tower, not a bruiser trading chip damage on the side.",
   "10edbf65-457d-48d0-9151-9df5b4fcb40a": "Zinx support, 1/3/9 \u2014 your best line of the night: 9 assists, 432 mitigation/min (above your level), only 3 deaths. Nothing to fix in the play. Pick up Spectra to finish the core (Prophecy/Spectra/Orion, 52%). Your real lever is the shot-call: you had the vision and the frontline after the 28- and 42-minute primes \u2014 call the group-and-push there instead of letting the team scatter to look for more picks."
  }
 },
